{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ae339fef-3236-4b95-b08a-1dfbf218fe35","content":"The template has a solid foundation but isn't quite ready to publish. Here are the issues:\n\n**Must fix:**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for tooling/validation support.\n- **Missing `description`** — Required for NuGet discoverability. Without it, the listing will be blank.\n- **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces`** — The parameter is defined but never wired into the project files. It won't actually change the target framework. You need a `replaces` property (e.g., `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"`) or a generated symbol to substitute it into the `.csproj`.\n\n**Recommended:**\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Strongly recommended when publishing to NuGet. It groups related templates (e.g., across languages/versions).\n- **No `preferNameDirectory`** — Typically `true` for project templates so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory.\n- **No `postActions`** — Consider adding a `restore` post-action so `dotnet new` automatically runs `dotnet restore`.\n\nThe `Framework` symbol issue is the most critical — as-is, the `--Framework` flag would be accepted but silently do nothing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6061294b-72a0-4ab4-a9b0-ea3fa8ffafcd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but recommended for tooling support. The standard schema URL is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for templates that may have multiple versions or language variants.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple templates share the same `groupIdentity`.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Common for project templates.\n\n5. **`defaultValue` for Framework is \"net9.0\"** — This is fine, but worth noting.\n\n\n6. **No `replaces` on the Framework symbol** — The Framework parameter won't actually update the target framework in the `.csproj` without a mechanism to wire it in.\n\n7. **Missing `description`** — There's no top-level description field, which matters for NuGet discoverability.\n\n8. **No `postActions`** — Not required but commonly used for things like restoring NuGet packages after template instantiation.\n\nThe most critical gaps for publishing are the missing `description` (important for NuGet listings), the Framework symbol lacking a `replaces` property (it's a functional bug that prevents the parameter from working), and no `groupIdentity` (which is recommended for NuGet). The `$schema` is nice to have but less critical. Let me focus on these key issues for the review.","outputTokens":807,"requestId":"0410:7874F:AA0C4C:D46758:6A012A78"},"id":"b81a2ba4-e68f-462b-882a-c615cb883621","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:02:03.119Z","parentId":"c6a45296-b4ac-46ab-9e28-cbaeffb2ac18"}
